summary.seg: This manuscript, copied probably in the 16th century, contains Liturgical texts and a Nomocanon.
It is formed of four parts; although clearly distinguishable for the script, the layout and also in terms of dimensions, they seem to be fairly consistent in terms of chronology and provenance.
The first part comprises a nomocanon in modern Greek, an akolouthia, a liturgical office promulgated by the Council of Constantinople in 1484 for those renouncing the Latin faith, and some prayers.

The second and the fourth part are both smaller and contain parts of the Liturgy of the Presanctified gifts, a communion evening service, for use on days when there is no Eucharist, such as weekdays during Lent.
The third part contains a part of a Euchologion, a prayer book for various services of the Byzantine rite.

The manuscript was owned by the English teacher, classical scholar and educational reformer William Henry Denham Rouse (1863-1950), fellow of Christ's College. He cited it as Nomocanon I in an article he published in 1899 about Folklore from the Southern Sporades ( Rouse 1899), where he mentioned that he had acquired it, with other three Greek manuscripts ( Cambridge, Christ's College, 264, 265, and 266) in the neighbourhood of the Greek Isle of Cos. A note on f. 2:4v confirms the provenance of the manuscript from the Dodecanese (Southern Sporades), as it attests that the codex, in 1723, was bought from a Kalymniot.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript exhibits two modern foliations in pencil, in Arabic numerals, in the lower margin, left, recto (here labeled respectively as 1 and 2). The second numbering exhibits twice the number 48 (2:48 and 2:48[a]): [i]-[ii] + 1:1-1:60 + 2:1-2:48 + 2:48[a] + 2:49-2:116 + [iii]-[iv].
supportDesc.collation: The condition of the manuscript does not allow to reconstruct completely the original collation, in particular for the first part of the codex. For part I of the manuscript it is possible to recognize with certainty only two quaternions; part II is formed by a ternion which lost the last leaf; part III is formed mainly by quaternions. ff. [i]-[ii], ff. 1:1-1:19, Quires 1-28, ff. 1:36-1:55 | Quire 36-1 | ff. 1:61-1:64, Quires 4-168, Quire 178-1 | ff. 2:115-2:116
supportDesc.condition: The manuscript suffered severe damage. Some leaves lost significant parts along the edges and were restored by means of paper strips ( ff. 1:42r-1:54v) or glassine (ff. ff. 1:1r-1:2v, 1:55r-1:56v, 2:116r-2:116v). Almost half of ff. 1:5r-1:5v has been lost. On various leaves ink faded due to water damage. Water stains are present throughout the volume, in particular on ff. 2:45r-2:108v. Insect damage is also detectable throughout the volume.

binding.p:
19th-century full leather binding over millboards, by Gray and son in Cambridge. There is a decorative blind tooling on the
covers. The title Greek MS. is tooled in gold on the spine.

history.provenance:
The manuscript came into possession of William Henry Denham Rouse (1863-1950) Rouse, W.H.D. (William Henry Denham), 1863-1950 certainly before 1899, when he published an article in which he cited it ( Rouse 1899); he acquired it in
Cos (see Rouse 1899).
history.acquisition: The codex was presented to Christ's College by W.H.D. Rouse Rouse, W.H.D. (William Henry Denham), 1863-1950 , Honorary Fellow of Christ's, in 1940 (see label pasted on the left pastedown).

handNote.p: ff. 2:1r, 2:5r-2:107v Hand C: a minuscule script, slanting slightly to the right, with moderate variation in letter size; passim there are flourishing tails in the margins (see e.e. f. 2:20r).
The text is written in brown ink, initials in red.
ff. 2:1v-2:4v Hand D: a minuscule script, characterized by variation in letter size, a cursive and exuberant ductus, and frequent flourishing tails in the margins.
The text is written in brown ink, initials in brown and red. Some letters are traced with a double stroke in black and red, and sometimes loops are filled in red.

decoDesc.decoNote: Decorated initials traced in black and red ink, with vergetal motifs, (see e.g. ff. 2:5r-2:5v), or palmettes (see e.g. f. 2:24r); initials in red or brown ink with vegetal motifs, see e.g. on ff. 2:18v-2:19r; an anthropomorphic initial on f. 2:20v.

additions.p: Passim there are jumble annotations, pen trials by hands which show low writing skills, see ff. 2:21r-2:21v.

On f. 2:4v there is an acquisition note in modern Greek, by a later hand, signed on 3rd October 1723 by a certain papas Ioannes, who says he bought the codex from a Kalymniot. A later hand wrote under the date in Greek numerals 1743, reading, wrongly, the 3rd number as Î¼Î (40) instead of ÎºÎ (20).

history.origin:
The script suggests a copy of this part of the manuscript
in the 16th century.
history.provenance: As the note on f. 2:4v attests, this part of the manuscript (at least) was probably in Kalymnos around 1723.
